lines.append('## Deeper Analysis And Research\n')
lines.append('### 1. The Shared Probe Bundle Was Real, But It Was Global\n')
lines.append('The recurring probe bundle from `stress-20260409-post-hardstop.out` consisted of these four global health queries:')
for q in PROBES: lines.append(f'- `{q}`')
lines.append('Those probes were not trying to find any specific chapter record. They were deliberately varied across fraternity names, universities, and field shapes to test whether the provider stack could successfully return *anything* representative. When the provider stack failed all four, the system marked preflight as degraded and **skipped chapter-specific fanout** for affected jobs. That is why rows such as `phi-gamma-delta-main / sigma-tau-chapter-university-of-washington / find_instagram` should have been read as “zero chapter-specific external queries were attempted because the provider layer was already unhealthy,” not “the system queried Sigma Chi for a Fiji chapter.”\n')
lines.append('### 2. The Largest Failure Class Was Not Search; It Was Bad Historical Inventory\n')
lines.append('The final failed-reason distribution makes this clear: `ranking_or_report_row=3427`, `year_or_percentage_as_identity=2570`, `school_division_or_department=170`, `history_or_timeline_row=137`, and `award_or_honor_row=3`. That means most of the jobs that “failed” in the final database were not legitimate fraternity chapter contact attempts. They were artifacts that should never have been in the contact lane. This matters because it changes the interpretation of the stress run: a large part of the night was spent teaching the queue to **refuse** work more accurately, not chasing real chapters poorly.\n')
lines.append('### 3. Throughput Increased Even While Providers Stayed Sick\n')
lines.append('Peak throughput (`104.40 jobs/min`) did not happen because providers recovered. It happened after queue correctness patches made the system more decisive about what **not** to search. In other words, high throughput later in the run mostly reflected faster triage, safer deferral, and clearer prerequisite enforcement, not a healthier external environment. That is why some late batches show strong jobs/minute while the dominant outcomes are still deferred repair, deferred provider degradation, and terminal no-signal.\n')
lines.append('### 4. There Was No Online Reinforcement Learning Loop During The Run\n')
lines.append('The stress path used `langgraph_primary` in all 21 recorded batches and `policy_pack=default` in all 21 recorded batches. There was no evidence of live policy-pack switching, online bandit exploration, or online reinforcement learning changing search behavior mid-run. The “learning” that happened during the six hours was deterministic and human-authored: telemetry exposed failure pressure, code was patched, and the same cohort was rerun. That distinction matters because the run’s improvements came from **architecture and queue policy changes**, not from a model autonomously adapting its own strategy.\n')
lines.append('### 5. What Still Consumes Risk After The Run\n')
lines.append('The final deferred queue shows the remaining risks clearly: '+', '.join(f"`{r['reason_code'] or '(blank)'}={r['count']}`" for r in deferred_reason_counts[:7])+'. The system is healthier because these are explicit, typed reasons rather than hidden thrash. But they still represent real follow-up work: a future run can only improve business yield further by either improving provider health, increasing authoritative school/chapter validation coverage, or draining the repair backlog.\n')
lines.append('## Change-Driven Adaptation During The Run\n')
lines.append('| Approx. phase | Observation from telemetry | Patch / decision made | Measured change |')
lines.append('| --- | --- | --- | --- |')
